  "topic": "DeFi fees & revenue over time",
  "summary": "Aggregate DeFi fees (total fees paid by users, equivalent to gross revenue) and protocol revenue (the subset retained by protocols/token holders) have grown roughly 100x since 2020. Per DefiLlama (as-of 2026-06-17), cumulative all-time DeFi fees are ~$111.1B and all-time protocol revenue ~$60.7B. Annual fees rose from ~$0.32B (2020) to ~$7.4B (2021), plateaued ~$7.6B-$9.0B through 2022-2023, then surged to ~$17.4B (2024) and a record ~$27.2B (2025). 2026 is at ~$9.7B through mid-June. Trailing-12-month fees are ~$24.9B and TTM revenue ~$14.0B. Current 30-day run-rate is ~$1.66B fees / ~$1.04B revenue (~$20B/$12.5B annualized). IMPORTANT CAVEAT: DefiLlama's aggregate 'fees' includes stablecoin issuers (Tether, Circle) and L1/L2 chains. Stablecoin issuers alone are ~39% of current 30d fees and chains ~8%; excluding both, 'pure' DeFi-protocol fees are ~$0.97B/30d (~$11.7B annualized). The largest fee generators today are stablecoin issuers Tether and Circle, followed by Hyperliquid (perps), Aave (lending), Lido (liquid staking), and DEXs (Uniswap, PumpSwap). Peak single-month fees were ~$3.26B in January 2025; ATH single day ~$238.7M on 2025-01-20. Confidence is high for DefiLlama-sourced figures (methodology consistent); medium for cross-source comparisons given differing definitions of what counts as 'DeFi'.",
